# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abaza-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abaza-language/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:abaza-language/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:abaza-language/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:abaza-language/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:abaza-language/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:abaza-language/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:abaza-language/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:abaza-language/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Abaza is spoken by approximately 35,000 people in Russia, where it is written in a Cyrillic alphabet, as well as another 10,000 in Turkey, where the Latin script is used.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] It consists of two dialects, the Ashkherewa dialect and the T'ap'anta dialect, which is the literary standard.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The language also consists of five subdialects known as Psyzh-Krasnovostok, Abazakt, Apsua, Kubin-Elburgan and Kuvin.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Abaza, like its relatives in the family of Northwest Caucasian languages, is a highly agglutinative language.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] For example, the verb in the English sentence "He couldn't make them give it back to her" contains four arguments (a term used in valency grammar): *he*, *them*, *it*, *to her*.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Abaza marks arguments morphologically, and incorporates all four arguments as pronominal prefixes on the verb.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] It has a large consonantal inventory (63 phonemes) coupled with a minimal vowel inventory (two vowels).
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] It is very closely related to Abkhaz, but it preserves a few phonemes which Abkhaz lacks, such as a voiced pharyngeal fricative.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Work on Abaza has been carried out by W.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Allen, Brian O'Herin, and John Colarusso.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Different forms of cultural assimilation contributed to its fall in use in areas of Russia, and over time its overall endangerment.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The language can be broken into five different dialects and has several unique grammatical approaches to languages.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language was at its peak usage in the mid to late 19th century.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Abaza speakers along the Greater and Lesser Laba, Urup, and Greater and Lesser Zelenchuk rivers are from a wave of migrants in the 17th to 18th centuries who represent the Abaza speakers of today.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The end of the Great Caucasian War in 1864 provided Russia with power and control of the local regions and contributed to the decrease in the popularity of pre-existing local languages prior to the war.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language was not a written language until the Latin alphabet was adopted in 1932–1933 to write it.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The Cyrillic script was later utilized to write the language in 1938.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] A small amount of books, pamphlets, and a newspaper were published in the Abaza language afterwards.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The Abaza language is spoken in Russia and Turkey.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Although it is endangered, it is still spoken in several regions in Russia.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] These include Kara-Pago, Kubina, Psyzh, El'burgan, Inzhich-Chukun, Koi-dan, Abaza-Khabl', Malo-Abazinka, Tapanta, Krasnovostochni, Novokuvinski, Starokuvinski, Abazakt and Ap-sua.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The vowels [o, a, u] may have a /j/ in front of it.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The vowels [e] and [i] are allophones of /a/ and /ə/ (respectively) before palatalized consonants, while the vowels [o] and [u] are allophones of /a/ and /ə/ (respectively) before labialized consonants.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The vowels [e], [o], [i], and [u] can also occur as variants of the sequences /aj/, /aw/, /əj/ and /əw/.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Abaza does not have the long low vowel found in Kabardian, preserving it as /aʕ/ or /ʕa/.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, there were attempts to write Abaza with the Arabic script, but none of these attempts took hold.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] In 1932, the first widely used Abaza alphabet was created using the Latin script.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Since 1938, Abaza has been written with the version of the Cyrillic alphabet shown below.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] The digraphs Лӏ and Фӏ are dialectal, and are therefore absent from the literary language and the official alphabet.
[src:abaza-language/abaza-language] Sultan Laguchev, a singer-songwriter famous in Russia, writes and performs songs in the Abaza language, including "Абыгъь гӏважьква" and "БаъапI бара." He has written an additional song in Russian entitled "Мы абазины" ('We are Abazins') about Abazinia.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] The **Abazins** (or **Abazinians**), also known as the **Abaza**, are an ethnic group of the Northwest Caucasus, closely related to the Abkhaz and Circassian peoples.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] Today, as a result of atrocities committed by Imperial Russia during the Circassian genocide, they live mostly in Turkey, Syria, Jordan, Egypt and in Karachay-Cherkessia and Stavropol Krai in the North Caucasus region of Russia.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] The Tapanta (ru:Тапанта), a branch of the Abaza, lived between the Besleney and Kabardian princedoms on the upper Kuban.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] Abaza people historically speak the Abaza language, a Northwest Caucasian language most closely related to Abkhaz, and more distantly related to the Ubykh and Circassian languages.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] There are two dialects of Abaza spoken in Karachay-Cherkessia: *Ashkharua* and *Tapanta*.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] The culture and traditions of the Abazin are similar to those of the Circassians.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] On many old maps Abazin territory is marked as part of Circassia (Adygea).
[src:abaza-language/abazins] According to the 2010 Russian census, there were 43,341 Abazins in Russia.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] An Abazin diaspora exists in Turkey, Egypt and in Middle Eastern countries such as Jordan and Syria, most of which are descendants of muhajirs from the Caucasian War with the Russian Empire.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] There is a significant Abazin presence in Turkey.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] An estimated 150,000 Abaza live in the provinces of Eskişehir, Samsun, Yozgat, Adana, Kayseri, and Sakarya, as well as İzmit and İstanbul.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] Most of them belong to the Ashkharua clan that fought against the Tsarist army and emigrated to Turkey after losing the battle of Kbaada (Krasnaya Polyana in today's Sochi), whereas the Tapanta clan fought with the Russian forces.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] A prominent example in Egypt is the Abaza family, a large Egyptian Abazin clan.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] Historically, the Abazin engaged in animal herding and some farming.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] The Abazins are dominantly Sunni Muslims.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] The Abazins first encountered Islam during their migrations to the Abazinia region via contact with the Nogais and other Muslim people.
[src:abaza-language/abazins] The Abazins adopted Islam via the influence of Muslim merchants and missionaries from the 16th to 19th centuries.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz is a Northwest Caucasian language and is thus related to Adyghe.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The language of Abkhaz is especially close to Abaza, and they are sometimes considered dialects of the same language, Abazgi, of which the literary dialects of Abkhaz and Abaza are simply two ends of a dialect continuum.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Grammatically, the two are very similar; however, the differences in phonology are substantial, it also contains elements characteristic of Kabardian; these are the main reasons for many others to prefer keeping the two separate, while others still refer to it as the Tapanta dialect of Abkhaz.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Chirikba mentions that there are possible indications that proto-Northwest Caucasian, could have divided firstly into proto-Circassian and to proto-Ubykh-Abkhaz; Ubykh then being the closest relative to Abkhaz, with it only later on being influenced by Circassian.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There is not an agreed number of speakers of Abkhaz, and there are widely different numbers.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] It is agreed that today most of the Abkhaz people do not live in Abkhazia.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In the census conducted by the Republic of Abkhazia in 2011, Abkhazians comprised 50.8% of the population, around 122,175 people; of these 92,838 spoke it natively.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Only two of the original dialects are still spoken in Abkhazia.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The Bzyp dialect is still spoken in its homeland northwest of Sukhumi, stretching from the Bzyp River to the western environs of Sukhumi and the Psyrtskha valley, whereas the Abzhywa dialect is spoken south-east of Sukhumi.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The rest of the Abkhaz speaking population inhabits other neighbouring areas.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The exact number of Abkhazians and Abkhaz speakers in Turkey is not clear.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The Turkish census denotes 13,951, but the figures are dubious, since the numbers of Abkhazians that came from the beginning of the 19th century to the middle of the 20th have been documented at around 30 thousand.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] *Ethnologue* gives 150,000 Abkhazians living in Turkey, of these 50,000 still speak the language.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The head of the Abkhaz federation says there are in between 500 and 700 thousand Abkhazians in Turkey.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Historically the dialects of Sadz, Ahchypsy and Tsabal were located in Abkhazia; Sadz being spoken from the Bzyp river to the Matsesta River, and further to the north-west bordering the Sochypsta River.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Today they are exclusively spoken in the northwestern part of Turkey, specially in the Sakarya province, it being spoken in 14 villages.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The other major place where Abkhaz is spoken is in Karachay-Cherkessia, where the Northern dialects are spoken, although there they are considered as a separate language and form the literary Abaza language.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] They are spoken by 37,831 people in Russia, mostly in the south of Stavropol Krai in the area around Kislovodsk, and in the upper Kuma river area.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz is also spoken as a minority language around the world.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There is a considerable number of Abkhaz speakers in Adjara in southern Georgia, with the diaspora concentrating itself around the capital Batumi, with about 982 people considering Abkhaz their first language.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In the Russian census of 2010, 6,786 speakers of Abkhaz were reported in Russia.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In Ukraine there are around 1,458 according to the 2001 census, but of these only 317 speak Abkhazian.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There were also communities in Syria, Jordan and Iraq with around 5,000 Abkhazians, although this number could reach 10,000 according to the Abkhazia's Foreign Ministry.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The biggest western diaspora is in Germany, with around 5,000 speakers, but other communities are found in countries such as the United States, United Kingdom, Austria, France, Belgium and so on.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The earliest indisputable extant written records of the Abkhaz language are in the Arabic script, recorded by the Turkish traveller Evliya Çelebi in the 17th century.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has been used as a literary language for only about 100 years.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] It was suggested that certain inscriptions on Ancient Greek pottery which had been considered nonsense are in fact written in Abkhaz-Adydge languages.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The methodology of the research was criticised and the results called improbable.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In 1918, Tbilisi State University became the first institution of higher education to teach Abkhazian language.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The founders of the university began to take care of the development and scientific study of the Abkhazian language.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] At the meeting of the Council of Professors held at Tbilisi State University in 1918, Ivane Javakhishvili noted the scientific importance of studying Caucasian languages.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In 1918, by the decision of the Council of Professors, Petre Charaia was invited to teach the Abkhazian language, and from 1925, this mission was continued by Dimitri Gulia and Simon Janashia.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Both Georgian and Abkhaz law enshrines an official status of the Abkhaz language in Abkhazia.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The 1992 law of Georgia, reiterated in the 1995 constitution, grants Abkhaz the status of second official language in the territory of Abkhazia — along with Georgian.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In November 2007, the de facto authorities of Abkhazia adopted a new law "on the state language of the Republic of Abkhazia" that mandates Abkhaz as the language of official communication.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The law is an attempt to amend a situation where up to a third of the ethnic Abkhaz population are no longer capable of speaking their ethnic language, and even more are unable to read or write it; instead, Russian is the language most commonly used in public life at present.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The literary language is based on the Abzhywa dialect.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In some form or the other, all dialects are richer in phonemes than the standard Abzhywa dialect.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The only dialects spoken in Abkhazia are Abzhywa and Bzyp.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Northern dialects which are the basis for literary Abaza are spoken in Karachay-Cherkessia, while the other dialects such as Sadz are spoken in Turkey due to Russian invasions in the 19th century.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] While most differences are phonetic, differences in the lexicon are present, although mostly due to exterior contact.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Bzyp contains the most preserved lexicon, with few borrowings.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abzhywa has adopted many loans from Kartvelian, specially Mingrelian; Sadz on the other hand has more words from Circassian.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Northern dialects in general have more loanwords from Persian, Arabic, Turkish and Circassian.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has a very large number of consonants (58 in the literary dialect), with three-way voiced/voiceless/ejective and palatalized/labialized/plain distinctions.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] By contrast, the language has only two phonemically distinct vowels, which have several allophones depending on the palatal and/or labial quality of adjacent consonants.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Labialised alveolo-palatal fricatives are found in the Bzyp and Sadz dialects of Abkhaz, but not in Abzhywa.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Plain alveolo-palatal consonants and the pharyngealised and labialised-pharyngealised uvular fricatives are unique to the Bzyp dialect.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The consonants highlighted in red and in brackets are the 4 kinds of labialisation described by Chirikba.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Found in the Bzyp and Sadz dialects of Abkhaz, but not in Abzhywa.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The nature of the vowels of Abkhaz is not clear.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Some linguists, characterise the vowel system as a 2 degree vertical vowel system; with the two vowels being distinguished by height, 'ә' being the high/close vowel, and 'а' being the low/open.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] This system would very closely resemble the one found in Adyghe.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The quality of 'ә' in this case, is usually represented as [ɨ] if the vowel is in a stressed position, and being unaffected by its neighbouring consonants.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Other linguists however, mainly Russian ones, describe the vowels differently.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] They describe the sound of 'ә' being completely different from [ɨ], and by their descriptions being closer to [ə].
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The 'а' is described as being particularly back, likely [ɑ].
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz has used the Cyrillic script since 1862.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The first alphabet was a 37-character Cyrillic alphabet invented by Baron Peter von Uslar.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In 1909 a 55-letter Cyrillic alphabet was used.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] A 75-letter Latin script devised by a Russian/Georgian linguist Nikolai Marr lasted for 2 years 1926–1928 (during the Latinization campaign).
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The Georgian script was adopted and used between 1938 and 1954, after that the initial Cyrillic alphabet, designed in 1892 by Dmitry Gulia together with Konstantin Machavariani and modified in 1909 by Aleksey Chochua, was restored to use.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The Latin alphabet in Abkhaz is currently not in Unicode.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Typical of Northwest Caucasian languages, Abkhaz is an agglutinative language that relies heavily on affixation.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] It has an ergative-absolutive typology, such that the subject of an intransitive verb functions identically to the object of a transitive verb.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Notably, Abkhaz expresses ergativity entirely through the ordering of subjects and objects within verb constructions rather than through overt case marking as most other ergative languages do.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] All Latin transliterations in this section utilize the system explicated in Chirikba (2003) (see Abkhaz alphabet for the details).
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz, being an ergative language, makes a strong distinction between transitive and intransitive verbs, as well as dynamic and stative.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs describe states of being, roughly analogous to copular phrases in English, as in дхәыҷуп (*d-x˚əčә́-wə-p* - "she is a child").
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs express direct actions, functioning more closely to standard English verbs.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs possess the full range of aspect, mood and tense forms, in contrast to statives, which do not.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Some verbs, called inversives, combine certain features of both stative and dynamic verbs.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Another important verbal distinction in Abkhaz is finite versus non-finite.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Finite verbs usually contain enough information to form a complete sentence, whereas non-finite verbs typically form dependent clauses.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Verb stems can be derived in a number of ways, including compounding, affixation, reduplication or conversion from another part of speech.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Roughly equivalent to the infinitive, or to a so-called "verbal noun," the **Masdar** form of the verb resembles the English gerund.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] It is formed by the addition of a specific suffix to a bare verb stem, -ра (*-ra*) for a dynamic verb and -заара (*-zaara*) for a stative.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] However, the fully conjugated personal Abkhaz verb forms are "templatic," with each grammatical distinction occupying a specific "slot" or "position" within the broader verb template.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Verbs are thus formed by the addition of various affixes to the verb stem; these affixes express such distinctions as transitivity, person and stative/dynamic quality, occupying rigid positions within the overall verb structure.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There is a high degree of agreement between verbs and other parts of speech.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Not all of these elements will necessarily co-occur in every verb.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The individual parts of verb morphology are addressed below.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The first prefixing element of the verb complex expresses either the subject of an intransitive verb in the absolutive construction, or the direct object of a transitive verb in an ergative construction.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The following table illustrates the various agreement markers which can occupy the first position.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] These prefixes can either be in their long forms, containing the letters inside the parenthesis, or in the short forms that do not contain them.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] If the stress falls on the prefix, the long form is used.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] If the prefix is not followed by a consonant cluster, the short form is used.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] If the stress does not fall on the prefix, the short form is used.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] It is also possible for the possessive prefix ҽы́- (*čə́-*) in a reflexive construction or the relative prefix иы́- (*jә́-*) in a non-finite construction to occupy this position.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The second position is occupied by the indirect object or by the prefix аи- (*aj-*) for reciprocal pronouns equivalent to "each other" or "one another" in English.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] This position accommodates a number of prefixes.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Any indirect object occurring after the one in the second position occupies this position instead; a possessive prefix of stative verbs can also be placed here.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Where a possessive prefix exists in the first position, the reflexive prefix is placed here.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] This position is occupied by preverbal elements which are not an explicit part of the verb stem.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Preverbal elements that are explicitly attached to the verb stem take this position.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The agreement marker corresponding to the agent (the subject of a transitive verb) takes this position.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The negation prefix m- occupies this position in a dynamic verb construction.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The causative prefix r- takes the final position before the verb stem.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The first of the suffixing elements expresses adverbial information relating to "inside" (-la) or "outside" (-aa).
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Several aspect markers occupy this position as suffixes.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Several tense markers occupy this position, dependent upon whether the verb in question is stative or dynamic.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs have a richly developed tense paradigm incorporating tense and aspect distinctions.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The table below illustrates these various dynamic tense forms using the verb агара (*agara* – "to take").
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs, by contrast, lack this rich tense system, as illustrated below using the verb а́цәара (*ácºara* - "to be sleeping").
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The negation prefix m- occupies this position in a stative verb construction.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The final position in the verb complex can accommodate any one of several mixed purpose markers.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The **imperative** takes a few possible forms, depending upon the type of verb.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Dynamic verbs form the imperative by the addition of agreement suffixes to a bare verb stem; intransitives include the subject and indirect object makers, whereas transitives include the direct object and absolutive.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Stative verbs form the imperative simply by adding the durative suffix -z to the verb stem.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz lacks diathetic opposition, and as such there is no true passive voice distinction.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Like verbs, Abkhaz nouns are formed by the addition of various prefixes and suffixes to a static noun stem.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Noun stems can be derived according to several different processes, including compounding, reduplication, or the addition of a derivational affix.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The affixes mark number, definiteness and possession, as well as some case-like elements.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] As with verbs, not all of these elements can occur at the same time.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The individual parts of noun morphology are addressed below.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There is a range of definiteness in Abkhaz.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Those articles adhering to definite/generic categories appear as prefixes in the broader noun structure, whereas the indefinite is suffixed.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The absence of either article affix implies a zero reference implying universal quantifiers, or to express the total lack of a referent.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Definite and indefinite affixes may appear together in the same noun, implying that the referents are meant as a group or body.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There are some semantic differences in article usage between the different dialects of Abkhaz.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] These are possessive prefixes which express grammatical person and noun class.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] They come in two forms, the full and short ones.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The full ones contain the vowels inside the parenthesis, whereas the short ones do not.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] These few prefixes add numeric information to the noun complex.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Often, this takes the form of a numeral.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Inflectional suffixes can follow each other sequentially.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Abkhaz distinguishes singular and plural; the singular is unmarked, whereas the plural is indicated by noun class-dependent suffixes.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There are several pluralizing suffixes, but the two most commonly used refer generally to the human and non-human noun classes.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There are instances where explicitly human nouns take non-human plural markers.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] There are also several plural endings that are of much narrower use.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The clitic -гьы (*-g’ə*) functions as an in-built coordinating conjunction.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Nouns in Abkhaz are classified broadly according to a human/non-human paradigm, with the human class itself further subdivided into masculine and feminine gender.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Gender is a fairly weak concept in Abkhaz grammar, and gender distinctions undergo a fair degree of neutralization in several contexts, including personal pronouns, verb agreement and possession marking.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] This class and gender system distinguishes Abkhaz from the other Northwest Caucasian languages.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Although there is no special vocative declension, the prefix уа- (*wa-*), when attached to a noun stem, can express a vocative form.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Similarly, the suffix -a can be added to a proper noun ending in a consonant to communicate respect and endearment.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Pronouns are not inflected, and verbal agreement is generally sufficient to indicate grammatical person.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] It is common in everyday speech to use a short version of the pronoun which omits the suffix -рá (*-rá*), although this is done less frequently with third-person pronouns.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] In addition to noun-marking, **possession** can be indicated by adding the suffix -тәы́ (*-t’˚ә́*) to the short version of a personal pronoun.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Morphologically, adjectives are very similar to nouns, differing only in their syntactic function.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Similarly to nouns, adjective stems can be derived by compounding, reduplication and affixation.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] When used attributively, adjectives follow the noun that they modify.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Predicative adjectives, or those derived by suffixation, precede the noun.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The possessive prefix r- is used to show possessive agreement.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] These suffixes are added to the adjective stem to show agreement with the noun being modified.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The comparative form of an adjective is formed using the comparative particle аиҳá (*ajhá* - "more"), which precedes the adjective.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] The superlative form is indicated by the intensifier suffix -ӡа.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] Дарбанзаалак ауаҩы дшоуп ихы дақәиҭны. Ауаа зегь зинлеи патулеи еиҟароуп. Урҭ ирымоуп ахшыҩи аламыси, дара дарагь аешьеи аешьеи реиԥш еизыҟазароуп.
[src:abaza-language/abkhaz-language] "All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] The **Abzakh dialect** (Adyghe: Абдзахабзэ; Kabardian: Абдзахэбзэ) is one of the Adyghe language dialects.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] The Abzakh dialect is spoken by the Abzakh which are one of the largest Circassian population in the diaspora outside Republic of Adygea alongside Shapsugs.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Historically, Proto-Circassian possessed a distinct series of stops and affricates.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Phase 1 (Spirantization): The original affricates weakened into fricatives or glottal stops.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Phase 2 (Velar Palatalization): Historical palatalized velars shifted forward to fill the "gap" left by the changes in Phase 1.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] The following sections detail how these shifts occurred and provide comparative examples.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] The first major shift occurred in the Abzakh and Kabardian dialects, where the original affricate postalveolar consonants and affricate retroflex consonants underwent spirantization, becoming fricatives.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] One exception was that the original postalveolar ejective affricate [tʃʼ] ⟨чӏ⟩ did not just become a fricative; in Abzakh, it often debuccalized to a palatalized glottal stop ʔʲ ⟨ӏь⟩ (or simply ⟨ӏ⟩).
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] The following table details the timeline of this evolution specifically within Abzakh, showing how words shifted from Proto-Circassian, to an intermediate Proto-Abzakh stage, and finally to Modern Abzakh.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Later on, after the original affricates had become fricatives or glottal stops, a gap was left in the postalveolar position.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] In the majority of Circassian dialects (including standard Adyghe and Kabardian), the historical velar consonants shifted forward to fill this gap.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] The velars ⟨гь⟩ [ɡʲ], ⟨кь⟩ [kʲ] and ⟨кӏь⟩ [kʲʼ] became the new palato-alveolar consonants ⟨дж⟩ [d͡ʒ], ⟨ч⟩ [t͡ʃ] and ⟨кӏ⟩ [t͡ʃʼ] respectively.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] The following table demonstrates how these words are distinct in archaic dialects (like Shapsug) but have merged or shifted in Standard Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] The Voiceless velar fricative [x] becomes the aspirated Voiceless velar plosive [kʰ] (like English *c* in *car*, *cup*, *cop*, or *curse*) after the Voiceless postalveolar fricative [ʃ].
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] In this environment, the velar fricative undergoes hardening to become a plosive.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] This change only occurred in some Abzakh sub-dialects and in Bzhedug dialects.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] This should not be confused with the palatalized kʲ (like English *c* in *camera*, *cannon*, or *cow*).
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Khakurinokhabl sub-dialect of Abzakh, the instrumental case has the suffix -мӏе (-mʔʲa) or -ӏе (-ʔʲa) unlike other dialects that has the suffix -мкӏэ (-mt͡ʃa) or -кӏэ (-t͡ʃa).
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Standard Adyghe, The prefix зэкӏэ- means backward.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] In the Standard Adyghe, The prefix чӏэ- means under (toward under).
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо ахэмытэу нартхэр былымыхьэ кӏогъагъэх. Былымхэр къагъоти, къежьэжьыхи Къойданэм къэсыгъэх. Саусырыкъо дэмысыгъэу щытыти, къыхэкӏижьи, янэ дэжь къихьажьыгъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сыгъашх, тян, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо. — Сыгъашх, сыгъашх оӏо зэпыты, ущыс, модыкӏэ нартыхэр былым къахьи, Къойданым къэсыжьыгъэх, — къыриӏуагъ янэ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Нартымэ сырямыгъусагъэми, ащ къахьырэмэ анахьышӏуӏомкӏэ садэгощэн, тян, — ыӏуагъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Пӏэстэ шыӏэ щтыгъ, лы жъогъэ щтыгъ, щыбжьый-шыгъу атетэкъуагъэу ӏанэм къытыригъэуцуагъэх янэ. Саусырыкъо пӏастэр ыфызи, псыр къыӏифыгъ, лыр ыутхыпкӏи мылыхэр къыпигъэтэкъуи ышхыгъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ныбжьи нахь дэгъоу сыбгъэшхагъэп, тян, — ыӏуи къикӏижьыгъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо Тхъожъыем къытетӏысхьи, Къойданым кӏонэу ежьагъ. Саусырыкъо къакӏоу нартхэм залъэгъум, шӏэныгъэ иӏэу зы лӏы горэ ахэтыти: «Саусырыкъо мыгъо цӏыкӏур къэкӏозы, «фэсыжь апщи, нартхэ», зиӏокӏэ «тхьэуегъэпсэу» — шъуӏо нахь, «ахад» — шъумыӏо», — къариӏуагъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Зэриӏуагъэм фэдэу, тыдэкӏэ ахэхьагъэми «тхьэуегъэпсэу» къыраӏуагъ нахь, «ахад» къыраӏуагъзп.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Етӏанэ, Саусырыкъо губжъи, ежь зыфиӏорэр къыдэхъоу щытыти, щэщищ гъурӏи зишӏи шыӏэм зэтыригъэлӏагъэх.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Мэшӏо тӏэкӏу тэзгъэгъотырэр ӏэхьэгъу тшӏыщт зы ӏахьэкӏэ. — аӏуагъ нартымэ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сз шъозгъэгъотыщт, — ариӏуи, тау-таш горэм ӏугъо тӏэкӏу къыдихэу ылъэгъугъэти, Саусырыкъо ащ кӏуагъэ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Лэгъупышхом лы илъэу, пхъэцэӏитӏу, зы инырэ, зы цӏыкӏурэ пэлъэу, иныжъыри ащ къещэкӏигъэу пэӏулъэу къыӏухьагъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Машӏом икъыпэхыкӏэу хъущтыр Саусырыкъо ымышӏэу егупшысэу щытызэ, Тхъожъыер къэгущыӏи: «Уишыӏядзэ къыӏехи, упкӏэ цуакъэ сфэшӏ. Бажьэм фэдэу зызгъэзэщт, цызэм фэдэу сыкъэкӏощт, лъэгонжэмышъхьэкӏэ зесыдзыхынызы, пхъэцакӏэ иным уемыӏэу, цӏыкӏур къашти, тхьыны тыкӏожьыщт, — къыриӏуагъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Ишыӏядзэ къыӏихи, упкӏэ цуакъэ фишӏыгь. Къекӏуалӏи, Тхъожъыем лъэгонжэмышхьэкӏэ зыридзыхыгъ. Саусырыкъо пхъэцэкӏэ цӏыкӏум еӏэ шӏошӏызэ, иным еӏи, иныжъым тыригъафи, къыгъэущыгъ. Къэӏаби, Саусырыкъо рилъэшъохи шыр шъхьартӏупщэу хъугъэ, Саусырыкъуи иныжъым ипӏэшъхьагъ ӏилъхьагъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сыд уилъэгъунэу укъызыфэкӏуагъэр? — ыӏуи иныжъыр къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Шыӏэ тылӏэти мэшӏо тӏзкӏу схьынэу сыкъэкӏуагъ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Саусырыкъо ихьэгьо-шӏагъохэмэ ашышэу зы къаумэ къысаӏуи, устӏупщыжьыщт, — ыӏуагъ иныжъым.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Саусырыкъо ихьэгъо-шӏагъомэ ащышэу сэ зэхэсхыгъзу зы къаумэ къыосӏон, ау сэ ежь слъэгъугьахэп, — ыӏуагъ. — Саусырыкъо жьан щэрэхъыр къушъхьэм дарегъэхьые, къырарегъэфыхи, копкъышъхьэкӏэ еозы дефыежьы.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Саусырыкъо дихьыен ылъэкӏыщтэпти, ежь иныжъым жьан щэрэхъыр къушъхьэм дихьий, Саусырыкъо къырыригьэшэхыгъ. Иныр копкъышъхьэӏе къеуи, къыдифыежьыгъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ащ пэмыӏеу пшӏзрэ щыӏэмэ, къаӏо, — ыӏуагъ иным.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Цобзэ-шӏобзыр плъыжьыбзэу егъэплъызы, ыжэ кӏоцӏ делъхьазы егъэкӏуасэ аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ, — риӏуагь.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Иныжъым цобзэ-шӏобзыр плъыжьыбзэу ыгъэплъи, ыжэ дилъхьи, ыгъэкӏосагъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сӏукӏоцӏ хъутэ-плъытэщти, ыгъэусэни, сигъэтхъэжьыгъ. Ай нэмыӏеу сы пшӏэрэ? — ыӏуи къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ай нэмыӏеу, псыр егъажъо, псы жъуагъэм хэгьуалъхьэзы зегъэпскӏы.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Иныжъым гъоплъэ хьэкъуашъокӏэ псыр къыгъажъуи, машӏор ӏешӏыхьагъэу хэгъуалъхьи зигъэпскӏыгъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Шъохъу-тӏэхъум сигъалӏэщтыгъ, сыдэу ӏэзэгъу шӏагъо къысэпӏуагъ, сиӏял, — къыриӏуагъ. — Джыри сыд ышӏэу зэхэпхыгъэр?
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Ай нэмыӏеу, ыхыкъын къэсэу псым зыхигьэщтыхьати, щэщ-мэфищэ хэтыщтыгъэ, етӏанэ къыкъутэти къыхэкӏижьыщтыгъ, — аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Адэ ар таущытэу ыгъэщтытыгъэ, сыд ышӏэщтыгъэр? — ыӏуи иныжъыр къеупщӏыгъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Сшӏэрэп, зыгорэ еӏошъы псыр егъэщты аӏоу зэхэсхыгъэ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Псым хэуцу, — ыӏуи ытыкъыны къэсэу псым хигъэуцуагъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Ежь Саусырыкъо ышӏэу щытыти, щэщищым къэхъущт щтырыгъуӏир къышӏи, иныжъыр хигъэщтыхьагъ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Къеӏ, — ыӏуи къызеӏэм, мылыр къыгъэцӏацӏэу, къыгъачэу хъугъэ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] — Зэ зыгъэбыяу, щыгъупшагъэ сшӏыгъэ, — ыӏуагъ Саусырыкъо. — Саусырыкъо мылыр къыхичыти, псы къытыригъэлъадэщтыгъ, хьауарзэ хитакъоти, ыгъзщтыжьыти, къытыригъэсэжьыщтыгъэ.
[src:abaza-language/abzakh-dialect] Ащ фэдэу ышӏи: — Къеӏ, нныжъ, —зыреӏом, къьыкӏаӏи шъхьзкӏэ мылыр къыфэгъэхъыягъэп.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe is closely related to the Kabardian or East Circassian language; some reject the distinction between the two languages in favour of both being dialects of a unitary Circassian language, others argue they are closely related but technically distinct languages.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Despite phonological differences, Circassian languages are reciprocally intelligible, with speakers being able to communicate with varying degrees of efficiency.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] While the self-designation for both Adyghe and Kabardian language is *Adyghe*, in linguistic and administrative terms, "Adyghe" refers specifically to the language of the western tribes of Circassians, while "Kabardian" refers to the language of the two eastern tribes (Kabardians and Besleney).
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Ubykh, Abkhaz and Abaza are more distantly related to Adyghe.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe is also known as West Circassian or Lower Circassian.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe belongs to the Northwest Caucasian language family.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Glottochronological studies suggest that the common Proto-Northwest Caucasian language split into the Circassian, Abkhaz, and Ubykh branches roughly 5,000 years ago.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] One of the earliest attempts to create a standard for the Adyghe language was made by Natouko Sheretluk (Natouko Efendi), a Shapsug nobleman.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] He opened a madrasa in his native village of Bogundyr and compiled an Adyghe alphabet and grammar.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Leonty Lyulye, a Russian official who lived for many years among the Shapsugs, Natukhays, and Abadzekhs on the Black Sea coast, published a "Russian-Circassian Dictionary" and a brief grammar in Odessa in 1846.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Lyulye identified three dialects of Adyghe: "Kabardian", "Besleney", and a third he called "Common Circassian" (referring to the Western coastal dialects).
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] He tried to base his dictionary on this "Common" dialect.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Another pre-Soviet attempt was made by Wumar Bersey, an Abzakh.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] On March 14, 1853, he published the "Primer of the Circassian Language" (Adyghe Alphabet) in Tiflis (Tbilisi), based on the Arabic script.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] This date (March 14) is now celebrated annually as the "Day of the Adyghe Language".
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The standard register of Adyghe, known as Literary Adyghe (Adyghe: Литературабз, lit.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] 'Literature language'), was created by Circassian linguist Daut Ashkhamaf based largely on the Chemguy dialect, which was chosen for its simplicity.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] However, Literary Adyghe is a constructed dialect and is distinct from the natural Chemguy dialect, as there was significant input from the dialects of other tribes who remained in the Caucasus after the Circassian exile, spesifically the Bzhedug, Shapsug, and partly Abzakh.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the 1930s, Ashkhamaf even utilized the term "Bzhedug-Temirgoy dialect" to describe the basis of the literary language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] He argued that through the development of the literary language, these dialects were merging.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In some cases, literary dialect preferred words from other dialects over Chemguy words, such as Bzhedug "ӏэ" (hand) and "тхьэ" (god) instead of the Chemguy "ӏа" and "тхьа", as well as specific ordinal numbers and verb forms.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Thus, being supra-dialectal, literary Adyghe stands in contrast to territorial dialects and serves as the unifying literary form of the language for speakers of diverse dialects.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] There were proposals to merge Adyghe and Kabardian to create a single Circassian literary language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Another proposal was to select one of the two to serve as the single literary language for all Circassians.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] A rejected proposal by Circassian scholars argued for recognizing Kabardian as the sole literary language for all Circassians, as it had the most speakers.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] There were attempts to create a single unified alphabet for Adyghe, Kabardian, Chechen and Karachay-Balkar; but efforts failed because the leaders of the movement were accused of being "bourgeois nationalists" and executed in 1937.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Naloev, who was involved in the creation of the Kabardian alphabet, was executed by firing squad for alleged treason; he was rehabilitated posthumously in 1957.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Bolsheviks supported the creation of separate alphabets and grammars for the "Kyakh" (Western; the modern Adyghe language) and Kabardian, despite ongoing debates on unifying them.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Thus, Adyghe and Kabardian speakers could communicate easier orally as opposed to in writing due to different graphical representations and spelling rules.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] A more moderate proposal developed by the linguist M.A.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Kumakhov aimed to unify the alphabets and orthography without forcing a complete merger of spoken Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] This project proposed standardizing the representation of identical phonemes (using the same letter for the same sound where they currently differ, such as the Adyghe `жъ`vs.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The project was accepted by specialists at regional conferences in Nalchik and Maikop in 1998 and 1999.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] While the Parliament of the Kabardino-Balkarian Republic approved the project, the Parliament of the Republic of Adygea did not proceed to discuss it.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Cherkess) was a result of Soviet "ethnic engineering".
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The International Circassian Association (ICA) officially stated the goal of creating a "uniform Circassian language" in its 2015 congress resolution.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] There are many books written in or translated into Adyghe. А significant milestone was the publication of the "ABC-book of the Circassian language" by Wumar Bersey in Tbilisi on March 14, 1853, a date now celebrated as the Day of the Adyghe Language and Writing.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the early 20th century, reformist movements in Baksan led to the publication of religious and ethical textbooks such as "The History of Islam" (Мыслъымэн Тхыдэ) in 1918.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] A popular Adyghe translation of the Quran was made by Koshbaye Pshimaf Iskhak Mashbash.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The New Testament and many books of the Old Testament have been published in Adyghe by the Institute for Bible Translation in Moscow.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In 2020 a bilingual edition of Ecclesiastes was released in Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In 1908, Circassian Union and Charity Society in Istanbul began printing Adyghe language texts in the newspaper *Ghuaze.* Following this, the "*Adığe-Gazete"* (Adyghe Newspaper) was introduced in 1919.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In 1920, the bulletin "Diyane" was published in Istanbul using a Latin-based Adyghe alphabet.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the Middle East, a Circassian cultural society established in 1927 in El-Quneitra, Syria, published the newspaper "Mardzh" (Voice) from 1928 to 1932.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe Maq is the main Adyghe language newspaper in Russia.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] It is published in the capital of the Adyghe Republic, Maykop, five times a week.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The newspaper *"*Socialist Adygea" started in Krasnodar in 1926 and relocated to Maikop ten years later. he Adigean branch of the Union of Soviet Writers launched the literary almanac "Friendship" in Maikop in 1946.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] For younger readers, the children's magazine *"*Constellation" is published in the Adyghe language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Other early newspapers included *Qerehetlıq* (Black People) in 1924 and *Adığe Psevuç* (Adyghe Life) in 1926.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] According to the UNESCO 2009 map entitled "UNESCO Map of the World's Languages in Danger", the status of the Adyghe language in 2009, along with all its dialects (Adyghe, Western Circassian tribes; and Kabard-Cherkess, Eastern Circassian tribes), is classified as vulnerable.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe exhibits between 50 and 60 consonants depending on the dialect.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] All dialects possess a contrast between plain and labialized glottal stops.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] A very unusual minimal contrast, and possibly unique to the Abzakh dialect of Adyghe, is a three-way contrast between plain, labialized and palatalized glottal stops (although a palatalized glottal stop is also found in Hausa and a labialized one in Tlingit).
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Shapsug (Black Sea) dialect of Adyghe contains a very uncommon sound: a voiceless bidental fricative [h̪͆], which corresponds to the voiceless velar fricative [x] found in other varieties of Adyghe.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] This sound is only known to be used in the Black Sea dialect.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the Black Sea coast Adyghe dialects (e.g.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Shapsug dialect and Natukhai dialect) there exist a palatalized voiced velar stop [ɡʲ], a palatalized voiceless velar stop [kʲ] and a palatalized velar ejective [kʲʼ] that were merged with [d͡ʒ], [t͡ʃ] and [t͡ʃʼ] in most Adyghe dialects.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] For example the Shapsug words "гьанэ" [ɡʲaːna] "shirt", "кьэт" [kʲat] "chicken" and "кӏьапсэ" [kʲʼaːpsa] "rope" are pronounced in other dialects as "джанэ" [d͡ʒaːna], "чэт" [t͡ʃat] and кӏапсэ [t͡ʃʼaːpsa].
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In contrast to its large inventory of consonants, Adyghe has only three phonemic vowels in a vertical vowel system.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Adyghe alphabet contains some inconsistencies between visual representation and pronunciation which can be a point of confusion for learners.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] It is tempting to read the Circassian alphabet letters phonologically, but this is not always accurate.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] These letters are not part of the official alphabet, but they may appear in books that showcase the different dialects.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] For most of its history, Adyghe was an oral language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The folklore, particularly the Nart sagas, served as a repository for the language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Widespread literacy in Adyghe did not exist until the modern era and literacy was limited to a few people.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] From the 6th–5th centuries BC until the first half of the 15th century, the Adyghe people used the Greek alphabet, initially introduced through ancient Greek colonies and later reinforced by the Byzantine Empire and the Christian church.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Early forms of the Cyrillic alphabet were also used during this period due to Russian influence.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] During the 13th to 15th centuries, the development of relations with the Genoese Republic led to some use of the Italian (Latin) script.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the 14th century, along with Islam, the Arabic script was adopted for Adyghe.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] It was referred to as Ajam**,** a writing system for the native language based on the Perso-Arabic script.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Since Adyghe has many more consonants than Arabic, the Ajam system required adding special diacritical marks or inventing new letters to represent sounds.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Early attempts to write Adyghe in modern Cyrillic started as early as 1829 and were followed by similar attempts.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In 1853, the Adyghe educator Umar Bersey published the first "Primer of the Circassian Language" based on the Arabic script.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Over the following decades, several authors attempted to further improve the Adyghe Arabic orthography.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The most successful attempt was the alphabet created by Akhmetov Bekukh.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In this version, letters were designated for vowel sounds, and the orthography was transformed from an "Impure abjads to a true alphabet.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In 1918, on the initiative of the Kuban Revolutionary Committee, a primer was published in Yekaterinodar.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] This official endorsement resulted in a literary boom in Adyghe and the publication of various newspapers, textbooks and other literature, including the *Adyghe Maq*, the main Adyghe language newspaper established in 1923.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] During the abovementioned decades, parallel with this process, the Perso-Arabic orthography had also been standardized for the sister Circassian language of Kabardian.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Although very similar in many aspects, there were minor variations, in which letters were included based on each respective phonology, and there were minor differences in presentation of a few consonants as well.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Arabic script was used until 1927, when as a part of the Soviet "Latinisation" campaign, a Latin-based alphabet was adopted.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Yakovlev and the Adyghe scholar Daud Ashkhamaf.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the late 1930s, the script was converted to Cyrillic to align with Russian.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the diaspora, a new Latin alphabet based on the Turkish alphabet was designed to better facilitate Adyghe and Kabardian education in Turkey, named the ABX alphabet.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe, like all Northwest Caucasian languages, has a basic subject–object–verb typology and is characterised by the ergative construction of sentences.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Turkey hosts the largest Circassian population, but the language lacks any legal recognition.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] However, after the collapse of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of the modern republic, these schools were banned by the Kemalists.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Following the "Citizen, Speak Turkish!" campaign and the closure of Circassian schools, the language was confined to the home.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In educational settings, speaking Adyghe was strictly banned.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Students faced physical punishment and psychological alienation for speaking Adyghe, including during recess and outside of school grounds.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] To enforce this, teachers formed "discipline committees" made up of student informants.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Publishing in the language also faced state pressure; cultural magazines had to remove Circassian lyrics from traditional songs and publish only the musical notes to avoid government retribution.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Consequently, while the older generation retains fluency, proficiency among those under 50 is significantly diminished.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In a study, Nusret Baş (Бажь Нусрэт), the then-president of the Federation of Circassian Associations, estimated that about 5% of Circassians in Turkey (including people of Circassian descent) speak their native language fluently.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Linguistically, the Adyghe spoken in Turkey exhibits distinct features as it was not subject to the standartisation policies in the Caucasus.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] It contains archaic vocabulary lost in the Caucasus, alongside Turkish loanwords.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] While the Chemguy dialect forms the basis of the literary language in the Republic of Adygea, the majority of the diaspora in Turkey speaks the Abzakh and Shapsug dialects (as well as Kabardian), alongside smaller numbers of Bzhedug and Hatuqay speakers.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Hatuqay dialect is spoken only in Turkey.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In some cases, the physical mixing of different tribes led to dialectal convergence.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Frequent intermarriages between dialect groups led to the use of a mixed Adyghe koine or the dominance of one dialect in multi-tribal areas.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In some cases, the boundaries between dialects became blurred, resulting in a hybrid oral communication style, sometimes even including hybrids with Kabardian or Abaza.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Due to assimilation, Adyghe speakers in Turkey sometimes use Turkish terms for numbers, days of the week, months, and colors.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Significant changes occurred following Turkey's European Union accession process in the early 2000s.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The language policy was liberalized, which prompted revival efforts.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In 2012, the Ministry of National Education introduced "Living Languages and Dialects" as an elective course for secondary schools, allowing Adyghe to be taught in public schools.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Classes are only opened if a set minimum number of students apply, and bureaucratic hurdles regarding application windows often hinder access to these classes.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Teachers are subject teachers with basic language skills rather than trained philologists, and they receive limited training in language pedagogy.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Educational materials are imported from Adygea and are designed for native speakers, making them difficult to adapt for diaspora students who are learning Adyghe as a second language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] During the COVID-19 pandemic, transnational online courses were organized in collaboration with institutions in Russia, allowing students in Turkey, Jordan, and Germany to be taught by teachers directly from the Caucasus.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Düzce University has a Department of Caucasian Languages and Cultures, which offers "Circassian Language and Culture" programs, including the teaching of Adyghe in Cyrillic, as the surrounding region is inhabited largely by Shapsug and Abzakh Circassians.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Boğaziçi University began offering elective Adyghe courses in 2013.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] A significant debate persists in the Turkish diaspora regarding orthography of Adyghe.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Federation of Caucasian Associations (KAFFED) adopted the Cyrillic alphabet in 2004 to maintain continuity with the homeland, but other groups advocate for a Latin-based script to facilitate easier learning for Turkish speakers.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] This dispute intensified significantly when the Turkish Ministry of Education approved a Latin-based alphabet, called the ABX Latin Alphabet, for elective Circassian language courses in public schools, effectively creating a dual-alphabet system alongside the existing Cyrillic curriculum.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] KAFFED vehemently opposed this decision, arguing that it creates confusion and severs cultural ties with the autonomous republics in the Caucasus.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Demonstrations were at Ministry of Education offices across the country with slogans including "Hands off my alphabet," "We want our mother tongue's alphabet" and "How does Arabic in Latin letters sound?".
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Ubykh people in Turkey, who originally possessed their own distinct language, largely integrated with the Adyghe during their exile and adopted the Adyghe language as their own.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Ubykh language went extinct in 1992; today Ubykh people speak Adyghe or Turkish.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe State University is working to document Adyghe language and folklore in Turkey.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Circassian community in Israel, concentrated in the Circassian towns of Kfar Kama and Rehaniya, is considered to have one of the highest levels of language maintenance in the diaspora.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe serves as the language of daily communication in the home, school, and public spaces.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In 1958-1959, Israeli Circassians made contact for the first time with Circassians in the Caucasus and requested literary material in Adyghe, which they received.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In 1976, the Adyghe language was introduced into the official school curriculum.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] It is a compulsory subject from 6th grade onward, and utilizes textbooks based on the literary standard of the Republic of Adygea.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Despite the dominance of the Shapsug dialect in speech, the written language taught in schools utilizes the Cyrillic alphabet and the Chemguy-based literary standard.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Kfar Kama is inhabited by the Shapsug tribe, while Rihaniya is inhabited by the Abzakh tribe.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Israeli variety of Adyghe also contains unique neologisms.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Even in diaspora communities with highly preserved spoken fluency, such as the compact Circassian settlements in Israel, literacy is a significant challenge; one survey showed that while 81.7% of respondents had advanced speaking proficiency, only 12% reported writing proficiency.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In Jordan, the Adyghe language has historically enjoyed a relatively privileged status, though it currently faces significant pressure, as Arabic has become the dominant language for the younger generation, and the Adyghe language is often restricted to symbolic functions or domestic use.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Consequently, Adyghe in Jordan serves more as a folkloric marker of identity than a functional tool for daily communication.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language in Jordan is currently classified as severely endangered due to a rapid disruption in intergenerational transmission.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The decline of the language was triggered by migration, urbanization, and the dispersion of the Circassian population among the Arabic-speaking majority.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] For example, the expansion of Amman in the early 1900s transformed predominantly Circassian farming villages into diverse urban centres inhabited by Arabs, causing Circassians to become a minority in their original settlements.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Today, Arabic has almost entirely ousted Circassian as the primary language of communication within the home.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Surveys indicate that 21% of children use Circassian at home.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Because schools historically used Arabic as the sole medium of instruction, Circassian parents began speaking Arabic at home to ensure their children would not struggle academically.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Adyghe is taught in Prince Hamza Ibn Al-Hussein Secondary School, a school for Jordanian Circassians in Jordan's capital city of Amman.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] This school, established by Circassians with support from King Hussein of Jordan, is one of the first schools for the Adyghe communities outside Circassia.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] It has around 750 Jordanian Adyghe students, and aims to preserve the Adyghe language and traditions among future generations.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The diaspora in Jordan has produced dictionaries and linguistic works, such as a Circassian-Arabic dictionary published in 1988.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Circassian Charity Association of Jordan also sponsors a school between Naur and Wadi Al-Seer that teaches the language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Historically, various dialects were spoken by immigrants, including Shapsug, Bzhedug, (and Kabardian), but over time these dialects have merged.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Historically, the Golan Heights served as a centre for Circassian language preservation prior to the 1967 war.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the 1920s and 1930s, the "Circassian Society of Education and Union" in Quneitra published the newspaper *Mardj* in Circassian (using the Latin script), Arabic, and French, and established a school that taught the language alongside general subjects.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In the late 20th century, the Circassian Charity Association in Damascus operated informal language circles to teach the Cyrillic script and preserve oral traditions.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] However, the language has declined due to the lack of state-supported education and the dominance of Arabic in all public spheres.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] After the Syrian defeat in the war, the Circassian population largely fled the Golan Heights region, which was occupied by the Israeli Army.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Many of Syria's ethnic Circassians have left the country and have repatriated to Adygea, Kabardino-Balkaria and Karachay-Cherkessia, as well as to partially recognised Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Circassian American community is multilingual, speaking languages including English, Circassian (Adyghe, Kabardian), and Arabic.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] However, the community is currently experiencing a significant language shift away from their ethnic Adyghe language and toward English.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] English is the dominant language used in almost all public and social domains, utilized universally in the workplace and overwhelmingly with neighbors, non-Circassian friends, and even among Circassian peers.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language remains preserved primarily within the home, specifically in intergenerational communication.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Circassian is predominantly spoken by the elder members of the community and is the primary language used when younger generations address their grandparents, representing over 52% of these interactions.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] A study found that a large majority of the New Jersey Circassian community (81.5%) agrees that learning the Circassian language is essential for maintaining their ethnic identity.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] However, some Circassian Americans have abandoned Adyghe fluency as redundant, focusing instead on Adyghe Khabze, traditional dances and folklore.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The Circassian Benevolent Association (CBA) hosts a Sunday school where volunteers teach the Circassian language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In recent years, growing political pressure and the criminalization of civil society initiatives in Russia have forced many scholars and language activists to relocate, shifting the epicenter of Circassian language activism and cultural preservation to countries abroad, including the United States.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Following the Circassian Genocide and expulsion in 1864, the majority of Adyghe speakers were scattered across the Ottoman Empire.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The language spoken in the diaspora has diverged from the literary forms in the Caucasus.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Diaspora communities often use Arabic or Turkish loanwords where the literary language uses Russian ones.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The linguistic divergence between the Adyghe language spoken in the historical homeland and the language spoken by the diaspora, particularly in Turkey and the Middle East, is the result of over a century and a half of isolated development.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] This isolation, combined with the mixing of various dialects and the strong influence of local languages like Turkish and Arabic, led to significant phonetic, lexical, and semantic differences.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Some native Adyghe words acquired entirely new meanings in the diaspora.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The word *гу*, which historically means "wagon" or "cart" in the literary language, has evolved to mean "automobile" or "car" among diaspora speakers.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Similarly, the word *ин* (big) is used in the diaspora to refer to an "elder," replacing the literary term *нэхъыжь*.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Due to intense influence of the Russian language, Russian loanwords in standart Adyghe are left exactly as is and not adapted to the language in terms of spelling or pronouncation.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Turkish linguistic influence led to the creation of calques (literal translations) for modern concepts.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In some extreme cases, diaspora speakers even attach Turkish grammatical suffixes, such as the past tense *-miş* or the subjunctive *-dı*, directly to Adyghe roots, though native speakers often recognize these constructions as "non-Adyghe".
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] While the spoken and folkloric language of the diaspora evolved independently, this isolation has begun to diminish.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] With the advent of the internet and social media, the younger and middle generations in the diaspora are increasingly interacting with the Cyrillic-based literary language of the homeland.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] This exposure is initiating a slow but inevitable "literaturization" of the diaspora's language, gradually aligning their written and official communication with the literary standard.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] When conversing in Turkish, diaspora Circassians frequently embed native Adyghe terms to refer to specific traditional and unique cultural conventions, or use them as in-group slang.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Besides native vocabulary, the Adyghe language has accepted loanwsome ords from Turkic, Arabic, Persian, Russian and other languages.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] The appearance of Turkic loanwords in the Adyghe language can be dated to the 14th century due to interactions with the Golden Horde and Crimean Khanate.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] By the mid-19th century; Arabic words had begun to enter the language.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] Words such as *chapych* (kopeck) are pre-revolutionary loans from Russian.
[src:abaza-language/adyghe-language] In old borrowings, as a rule, the phonetic composition of borrowed words was adapted to the phonological system of the Adyghe language.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] An **affricate** is a consonant that begins as a stop and releases as a fricative, generally with the same place of articulation (most often coronal).
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] It is often difficult to decide if a stop and fricative form a single phoneme or a consonant pair.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] English has two affricate phonemes, /t͡ʃ/ and /d͡ʒ/, generally spelled *ch* and *j*, respectively.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] However, voiced affricates other than [d͡ʒ] are relatively uncommon.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] For several places of articulation they are not attested at all.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Much less common are labiodental affricates, such as [p͡f] in German, Kinyarwanda and Izi, or velar affricates, such as [k͡x] in Tswana (written *kg*) or in High Alemannic Swiss German dialects.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Worldwide, relatively few languages have affricates in these positions even though the corresponding stop consonants, [p] and [k], are common or virtually universal.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Also less common are alveolar affricates where the fricative release is lateral, such as the [t͡ɬ] sound found in Nahuatl and Navajo.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Some other Athabaskan languages, such as Dene Suline, have unaspirated, aspirated, and ejective series of affricates whose release may be dental, alveolar, postalveolar, or lateral: [t̪͡θ], [t̪͡θʰ], [t̪͡θʼ], [t͡s], [t͡sʰ], [t͡sʼ], [t͡ʃ], [t͡ʃʰ], [t͡ʃʼ], [t͡ɬ], [t͡ɬʰ], and [t͡ɬʼ].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Affricates are transcribed in the International Phonetic Alphabet by a combination of two letters, one for the stop element and the other for the fricative element.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In order to clarify that these form a single consonant, a tie bar may be used.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] The tie bar appears most commonly above the two letters, but may be placed under them if it fits better there, or simply because it is more legible.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] This is derived from the IPA convention of indicating other releases with a superscript.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] However, this convention is more typically used for a fricated release that is too brief to be considered a true affricate.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Ligatures ⟨, , , /, ⟩ for the non-coronal affricates [pɸ] [bβ], [pf] [bv], [cç] [ɟʝ], [kx] [ɡɣ]/[gɣ], [qχ] [ɢʁ] have also been used.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Any of these notations can be used to distinguish an affricate from a sequence of plosive plus fricative, which is contrastive in languages such as Polish.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] However, in languages where there is no such distinction within a syllable, such as English or Turkish, a simple sequence of letters such as ⟨tʃ⟩ is commonly used, with no overt indication that they form an affricate.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In such cases the syllable boundary may be written to distinguish the plosive-fricative sequence in *petshop* /ˈpɛt.ʃɒp/ from the similar affricate in *ketchup* /ˈkɛtʃʌp/.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In other phonetic transcription systems, such as the Americanist system, affricates may be transcribed with single letters.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Single letters may also be used with phonemic transcription in IPA: [tʃ] and [dʒ] are sometimes transcribed with the symbols for the palatal stops, ⟨c⟩ and ⟨ɟ⟩, for example in the IPA *Handbook*.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] The exact phonetic difference varies between languages.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In stop–fricative sequences, the stop has a release burst before the fricative starts; but in affricates, the fricative element *is* the release.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Phonologically, stop–fricative sequences may have a syllable boundary between the two segments, but not necessarily.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In English, /ts/ and /dz/ (*nuts*, *nods*) are considered phonemically stop–fricative sequences.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] They often contain a morpheme boundary (for example, *nuts* = *nut* + *s*).
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] The English affricate phonemes /t͡ʃ/ and /d͡ʒ/ do not contain morpheme boundaries.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] The /t/ in 'worst shin' can be elided: [wɜː(ɹ)sʃɪn].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Stop–fricatives can be distinguished acoustically from affricates by the rise time of the frication noise, which is shorter for affricates.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] When affricates are geminated, it is the duration of the plosive closure that is lengthened, not that of the frication.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] For example, /t͜sː/ is pronounced [tːs], not *[tsː].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Polish has been reported to favour phonological gemination through rearticulation of the affricate, rather than the common method of lengthening the plosive closure.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In the case of coronals, the symbols ⟨t, d⟩ are normally used for the stop portion of the affricate regardless of place.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] For example, ⟨t͡ʂ⟩ is commonly seen for ⟨ʈ͡ʂ⟩, ⟨t͡ʃ⟩ for ⟨t̠͡ʃ⟩ and ⟨t͡θ⟩ for ⟨t̪͡θ⟩.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] The exemplar languages are ones that have been reported to have these sounds, but in several cases, they may need confirmation.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] The Northwest Caucasian languages Abkhaz and Ubykh both contrast sibilant affricates at four places of articulation: alveolar, postalveolar, alveolo-palatal and retroflex.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] They also distinguish voiceless, voiced, and ejective affricates at each of these.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] When a language has only one type of affricate, it is usually a sibilant; this is the case in e.g.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Arabic ([d̠ʒ]), most dialects of Spanish ([t̠ʃ]), and Thai ([tɕ]).
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Itene, Oro Win, Sangtam, and Wari' have a dental stop with bilabial trilled release [t̪ʙ̥].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Although most affricates are homorganic, Navajo and Chiricahua Apache have a heterorganic alveolar-velar affricate [tx].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Itene, Oro Win, Sangtam, and Wari' have a voiceless dental bilabially trilled affricate [t̪ʙ̥] (see Trilled affricate).
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Other heterorganic affricates are reported for Northern Sotho and other Bantu languages such as Phuthi, which has alveolar–labiodental affricates [tf] and [dv], and Sesotho, which has bilabial–palatoalveolar affricates [pʃ] and [bʒ].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] The coronal and dorsal places of articulation attested as ejectives as well: [tθʼ, tsʼ, tɬʼ, tʃʼ, tɕʼ, tʂʼ, c𝼆ʼ, kxʼ, k𝼄ʼ, qχʼ].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Several Khoisan languages such as Taa are reported to have voiced ejective affricates, but these are actually *pre*-voiced: [dtsʼ, dtʃʼ].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Affricates are also commonly aspirated: [ɱp̪fʰ, tθʰ, tsʰ, tɬʰ, tʃʰ, tɕʰ, tʂʰ], murmured: [ɱb̪vʱ, dðʱ, dzʱ, dɮʱ, dʒʱ, dʑʱ, dʐʱ], and prenasalized: [ⁿdz, ⁿtsʰ, ᶯɖʐ, ᶯʈʂʰ] (as in Hmong).
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Labialized, palatalized, velarized, and pharyngealized affricates are also common.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Affricates may also have phonemic length, that is, affected by a chroneme, as in Italian and Karelian.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In phonology, affricates tend to behave similarly to stops, taking part in phonological patterns that fricatives do not.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Kehrein (2002) analyzes phonetic affricates as phonological stops.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] A sibilant or lateral (and presumably trilled) stop can be realized phonetically only as an affricate and so might be analyzed phonemically as a sibilant or lateral stop.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In that analysis, affricates other than sibilants and laterals are a phonetic mechanism for distinguishing stops at similar places of articulation (like more than one labial, coronal, or dorsal place).
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] For example, Chipewyan has laminal dental [t̪͡θ] vs. apical alveolar [t]; other languages may contrast velar [k] with palatal [c͡ç] and uvular [q͡χ].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Affricates may also be a strategy to increase the phonetic contrast between aspirated or ejective and tenuis consonants.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] According to Kehrein (2002), no language contrasts a non-sibilant, non-lateral affricate with a stop at the same place of articulation and with the same phonation and airstream mechanism, such as /t̪/ and /t̪θ/ or /k/ and /kx/.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In feature-based phonology, affricates are distinguished from stops by the feature [+delayed release].
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Affrication (sometimes called *affricatization*) is a sound change by which a consonant, usually a stop or fricative, changes into an affricate.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] In rare instances, a fricative–stop contour may occur.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] This is the case in dialects of Scottish Gaelic that have velar frication [ˣ] where other dialects have pre-aspiration.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] For example, in the Harris dialect there is *seachd* [ʃaˣkʰ] 'seven' and *ochd* [ɔˣkʰ] 'eight' (or [ʃax͜kʰ], [ɔx͜kʰ]).
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Richard Wiese argues this is the case for word-initial fricative-plosive sequences in German, and coined the term **suffricate** for such contours.
[src:abaza-language/affricate-consonant] Awngi has 2 suffricates /s͡t/ and /ʃ͡t/ according to some analyses.
